05277nam a22008295i 9783110733006DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021950241  a97831107330067 a10.1515/97831107330062doi  a(DE-B1597)574779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aSOC0520002bisacsh1 aRyder, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Acoustical Unconscious :bFrom Walter Benjamin to Alexander Kluge /cRobert Ryder. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (X, 265 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInterdisciplinary German Cultural Studies ,x1861-8030 ;v3200tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Hearing Otherwise -- t1 Walter Benjamin’s Shell-Shock: Sounding the Acoustical Unconscious -- t2 Of Birds and Barks: Listening in on the Forgotten in Freud, Benjamin, and Tieck -- t3 Voices Carry: Benjamin and Arnheim on Radio -- t4 Glimpsing the World through Our Ears: Günter Eich and the Acoustical Unconscious -- t5 Clatter in Kracauer and Kluge: Politicizing the Acoustical Unconscious -- tConclusion: Toward a Genealogy of the Acoustical Unconscious -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs there an acoustical equivalent to Walter Benjamin’s idea of the optical unconscious? In the 1930s, Benjamin was interested in how visual media expand our optical perception: the invention of the camera allowed us to see images and details that we could not consciously perceive before. This study argues that Benjamin was also concerned with how acoustical media allow us to “hear otherwise,” that is, to listen to sound structures previously lost to the naked ear. Crucially, they help sensitize us to the discursive sonority of words, which Benjamin was already alluding to in his autobiographical work. In five chapters that range in scope from Tieck’s Blonde Eckbert, which Benjamin once called his locus classicus of his theory of forgetting, to Alexander Kluge’s films and short texts, where he develops what he calls “sound perspectives,” this monograph discusses how the acoustical unconscious enriches our understanding of different media, from the written word to radio and film. As the first book-length study of Benjamin’s linguistic, cultural-historical, and media-theoretical reflections on sound, this book will be particularly relevant to students and scholars of both German studies and sound studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aBenjamin.  aGerman media.  aUnconscious.  ahearing.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021 Englishz978311075412408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2021z9783110753899oZDB-23-DKU0 cEPUBz97831107330200 cprintz978311073777640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110733006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110733006/original  a978-3-11-075070-6  DG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1b2021  a978-3-11-075072-0  DG Ebook Package English 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOO